1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
What the hell? No, this is not happening.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Didn't you get the memo? It's Stare-Mageddon. Come on Stanley.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:16,000
Dwight is having maintenance done on the elevator today, and he was really on top of it.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Weeks ago, he started the Stare-Mageddon Awareness Campaign.

5
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:27,000
The idea was to get us prepared, both mentally and physically, for a day that hopefully comes once in a hundred years.

6
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:34,000
It's a...Mageddon! Come on! Come on Stanley, stay in it!

7
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:41,000
I put 17 damn years into this company, and now they're making me climb Stare Mountain!

8
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Our office has an unusually large number of unusually large people.

9
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:49,000
This is an abomination!

10
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:56,000
So when something as routine as elevator maintenance happens, and people are forced to expend cardiovascular effort,

11
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,000
we have to compare it to the end of time.

12
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Red alert! Red alert! The reviews are in, I repeat, the reviews are in.

13
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:20,000
What? I just got a text from my brother, ScrantonTimesTribune.com. There's a review of the documentary.

14
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:24,000
What does it say? I don't know, Phyllis. I just got the text and started screaming red alert.

15
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
The alert was already set to red because of Stare-Mageddon. You think I should set it to double red?

16
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,000
I think we should.

17
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:41,000
The Office, an American workplace airing on PBS next month, is a documentary following the employees of Scranton's own Dunder Mifflin Paper Company.

18
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:51,000
In the series, which will air starting in May, we get an in-depth look at many interesting local people.

19
00:01:51,000 --> 00:02:01,000
There's Kevin Malone, the full staffian accountant, Dwight Schrute, the head salesman, forever chasing a manager position he will never get.

20
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:07,000
What does Josh McAuliffe know about the paper business? He works for a news... thing.

21
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Auntie Bernard, the rudderless trust fund child slash middle manager, whose incompetence is emblematic of a declining American economy.

22
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Ouch. Sorry, Andy, that's...

23
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:23,000
It's okay. What the hell does he know?

24
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:29,000
A possible explanation for his lack of career focus is his surprising musical talent.

25
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,000
I want you to print that out for me.

26
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:32,000
I will.

27
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:39,000
Now that this documentary is coming out, my days at Dunder Mifflin are probably limited and, you know what, good.

28
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Because this is not what I wanted to do with my life. I wanted to be my generation's Lisa Loeb.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:56,000
Though it mostly focuses on the daily realities of office life, a lurid subplot reveals the hypocrisy of a local public figure, embroiled in a gay affair while preaching family values.

30
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Oh, which public figure?

31
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:02,000
I bet it's Katie Corrick. I've been saying this for years.

32
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,000
No, I think they mean more like a politician.

33
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:18,000
You own the building. Why can't you fix the elevator in the middle of the night? Who do I look like? Jackie Joyner, Kersy?

34
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:27,000
Well, I did say it would be an inconvenience. You should have called me from downstairs. We could have met in the lobby. It's time to go out on a sale. Here we go.

35
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Son, you lost your mind. I'm not going anywhere until you fix my elevator.

36
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:39,000
The buyer is your sister's friend. This is the printing paper for the entire school district of Lackawanna. You are coming, and that's an order.

37
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:48,000
You are not my damn boss and you never will be. Guess what? Never gonna happen. Pete, iced tea, three sugars, five creams.

38
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Good morning, 3x5. Coming right up.

39
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Well, we won't be late. I love you, Mom. Thanks.

40
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Thanks.

41
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:07,000
Oh, your mom's watching the kids tonight. So what are you two up to? Oh, embassy suites. Do not disturb sign on the door. Mommy and Daddy are on the floor.

42
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,000
I wish.

43
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:10,000
What then?

44
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:13,000
Oh, nothing that exciting.

45
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,000
Marriage counseling? Do you know, that is the only kind of counseling.
